review_blob: Nice, sweet rich brew a nice molasses red/copper color. Warming rich body, tan head that fades quickly. Bitter enough to balance the sweetness.

Nice brown color, pours with a light khaki head. Nutty, roasty flavors dominate with a bit of hop bitterness. Minimal to no ale yeast fruitiness - in fact I was surprised this is an ale. Reminds me more of a dunkel or other dark lager than an ale. Nice, easy drinker.

Glad I finally got to sample this. Black, sticky and viscous, just like it should be. Hoppy and sweet, lots of coffee and chocolate; raisins; prune; burnt popcorn; all those things you expect. Very nice but a bit overshadowed by some of the other brews sampled last night.

Thanks to Larry for a mouthfull of this one. Black as night, black as my cats furry ass but it tastes a lot better (or at least I hope so!).

Smooth, winey gestalt, warming alcohol flavors and raisiny background. Fragrant malty aroma.

Hop bitternes in the background with minimal hop aroma or flavor.

Cant drink much of this one, thats for sure, or at least not without taking a taxi home. Doesnt taste like 18% alcohol though.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: Amazing black with ruddy complexion - minimal tan head with little lacing. Thick, bittersweet body with some alcohol vapors. In a night of many tastings this one stood out - flavors of dark chocolate, molasses, brown sugar toffee and espresso. Sweetness beaten back evenly by assertive hoppiness.

Looks good, nice pour, thick sticky head.

Whats with the flavor though? Burnt grass, broccoli, some hints of used ashtray. Sickly sweet and extra heavy body.

Ill drink it but never buy it again.

Wow this is REALLY good. Wonderful, fragrant hoppy aromas waft from the minimal thin head. Very light, velvety carbonation.

Golden tawny color, slightly hazy. 

Sweet, but  balanced by an mellow hoppy bitterness. 

Plenty of peach, pine and grapefruit in the finish.

wow.

Budweiser from tahiti.

Sweet, highly carbonated, but a bit hoppier than expected. 

Tastes better in Tahiti, I think, at least its cheaper there!

Thin, watery body with minimal head. Cool black color but the flavor......yech. Sweet, sweet, sweet, with some vanilla and malt notes. No hop or roasty malt character whatsoverver. Not sure why this is considered a stout.
Black color, tannish head with spicy/smokey nose. Kind of thin body and very sweet, maybe too sweet for the bitterness level.

Golden color, pours with good carbonation though not like some Saisons. Actually sweeter, less character than expected. Honey and malt flavors; almost lagerlike which is weird. Medium body. Good, but not worth the $10.99 I paid for the sixer.
Nice, but unremarkable. Pale color, lightly fruity nose. Some clove, pear flavors, but again unremarkable. Light body.

Nice color, beautiful tawny amber. Big, sweet beer with plenty of alcohol. In fact, alcohol and boozy aftertaste is the dominant non-hop flavor. Just the way I like it. Bitter, hoppy flavor with resiny citrusy notes and good aroma. Excellent, another home run for Stone.

Dont drink more than one, Im warning you...
OK,  I guess. Dark golden color. Balanced sweetness, rather heavy body. Malty, honey aroma. Kind of unremarkable but pretty good for the price.
Below average euro lager. Nice party beer since its cheap at Trader Joes. Clear golden minimal head. No aroma. Flavor almost nonexistent. Some bitterness, I guess. Refreshing.
Some aroma. Minimal head. Pretty gold color. Some honey flavor. No aroma. Boring.

Tastes like pumpkin pie but not sweet. No bitterness, no body, minimal color, no body to speak of. tons of nutmeg flavor that overpowers any malt and what hop flavor may or may not have been there.

I like pumpkin pie and I like beer but this is neither. Cute novelty.

I dont know what to do with the other 5 beers, hopefully I can pawn them off at a holiday party or something.
Wonderful black color, light tan sturdy head that lingers for only a short time. Heavy, thick palate and minimal aroma. Sweet, with hints of caramel and toffee. A great stout.
Beautiful orange color, light, fleeting head and minimal fruity aroma. Crisp, refreshing acidity and thin palate.
Tawny, golden color, medium bodied. Drier and hoppier than many Octoberfest beers. A nice drinker thats not heavy and sweet. I like it.

beer_brewer_name: Yakima Brewing And Malting Co./Bert Grants Real Ales
review_blob:
Cloudy, with nice hop flavor and bitterness. Not as hoppy as the deScription would lead you to believe, which is nice.

Balanced actually, medium body.

Yum!
Black beer with dirty tan head. Sweet, heavy body but light on the alcohol. Wonderful flavors of coffee, molasses, toffee and other goodness.

I couldnt believe this was supposed to be an altbier when i had it at the Louisville airport on tap. No mouthfeel to speak of, high level of carbonation and not a whole lot of flavor. Barely passable.
Nice ruddy color, decent head and aroma. OK, a bit lacking in body and flavor, buit OK nonetheless. Good widespread beer.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob:
Cardboardy, clear with white minimal head on tap. No wheat, no yeast, no honey in the flavor or aroma. Kind of like a tasty budweiser, if you can imagine that.

Waste of $4.00

OK, I guess - This is the first Kolsch Ive had so I dont know what to expect. Hop flavor but no aroma to speak of (fresh?). Light golden color, not a whole lot of body. Kind of like a pilsner in overall flavor and appearance, but with some fruity notes.

On tap in Louisville, I forget the name of the pub. Nice, creamy thick body with rich sweet flavors of molasses, caramel and vanilla. Oaky, boozy aroma and finish. Nice thick head, a lot of fun and a nice change.
Creamy, malty body and light malt aroma. Nice amber color. A good easy drinker and something out of the ordinary.

Good, but Im not sure what makes it a porter - lager-like smoothness, sweet, almost too sweet. Minimal hop flavor, some light notes of roasted malt but barely noticeable. Blood-red in the light.

Pretty, but not a whole lot going on.

On tap - It had been a really long time since Id had one of these and in the meantime I forgot how good it tastes. Creamy mouthfeel and malty balance with background hop bitterness. Great amber color and soft finish.
On tap - This was quite good. Maybe not as assertively bitter as many IPAs on the market, but a nice background hoppiness that balances the sweet body. Awesome hop aroma (piney) and flavor (citrusy).

Meh...

Nice amber color, great to look at with minimal head. Light, yet somewhat sweet body, and minimal bitterness. An easy drinker, but nothing Id crave.
beer_name: Widmer Brothers Drop Top Amber Ale

review_blob: Nice, drinkable brew with a clean, dry finish and great hop aroma and flavor. Maltiness comes through but certainly hop-balanced. I really liked this one.
Decent Brownish ale, good full body and bitter flavor, but nothing hemp-like about it. Pretty average, nice label, though, and the concept is an attention-getter.
Crisp, hoppy flavor with notes of bread and honey? Aroma grassy, flat, not particularly interesting. Nice gold color. A middle-of-the-road Cesky pilsner

Pretty dark reddish color with a khaki head. Aroma was sweet, smooth, with hints of dates, figs and sugarcane.

Flavor smooth, clean, much lighter body than your usual Belgian, which makes it very drinkable.

Beautiful red color with off-white head and an exotic, winey aroma. Flavor is sour, balanced with malt, which is interesting, and assertive. Yeasty flavors underneath and a tinge of hops in the finish. Nice, outside-the-box brew. I like it.
On tap, golden orange color, hazy with a white head. Bright spicy carbonation and a light body with a drinkable flavor and wonderful aroma. Minimal hop intrusion on the yeasty goodness.

On tap, good American pale ale with that distinctive aroma and flavor of citrus and mint.  Slightly hoppier than most but a good combination of malt and hop flavors. Nice golden hazy color. I could drink several of these.
Assertive, caramelized porter with a roasted, bitter flavor and a heavy body and mouthfeel. Great flavor and beautiful dark red color in the glass. Nice porter.
Wow what a revelation. Im not a huge fan of st. Peters other beers but this was a knockout. Bitter, English IPA with a nice malty backbone and assertive hop flavor and aroma.  Truly awesome.
From the keg, which Ive never seen before. This really appealed to me - dark brownish ESB with minimal hop bitterness and a full, malty body with notes of vanilla and caramel. Nice beer.
Pours a pretty dark copper color with minimal head. Caramely, toasted notes in the flavor with a moderate balanced hop flavor. Somewhat heavy, but very nice.  Overall a good one.
Cloudy, golden copper. Not much head, nice malty aroma and a great bitter backbone. Bready, fruity flavor and a great sturdy body. Good stuff.
Nice brown color, light tan head. Soft, sweet aroma, soft sweet flavor with notes of caramel and some residual sweetness. Not much hop flavor, but some matching bitterness.
Pretty, golden lager with a definite Euro flavor. Nice hop aroma, balanced bitterness and an overall great mouthfeel and flavor. Finishes clean and smooth.
One of my favorite Mexicans. Crisp, clean taste of hops. Light body and nice mouthfeel. Good stuff for a hot day and probably the best of the Mexican lightweights.
Smells good, looks good, lightweight but doesnt taste so good. Nice in the heat and better than Corona. Crisp, dry finish with no skunk.

Dark, malty body with no head. Sweet roasty flavors but not a whole lot of body. Smooth, clean finish and no hop flavor.

A bit skunky, could be the blue bottle.

Beautiful black walnut color with hints of red in the light. Lght tan/off white head. Smooth, light flavor with hint of nutty roast. Very light body overall with minimal to no hop flavor.  Easy drinker.
